Two freshwater fish, Rasbora sumatrana ( Cyprinidae) and Poecilia reticulata ( guppy; Poeciliidae), were exposed to a range of eight heavy metals ( copper ( Cu), cadmium ( Cd), zinc ( Zn), lead ( Pb), nickel ( Ni), iron ( Fe), aluminium ( Al), and manganese ( Mn)) at varied concentrations for 96 h in the laboratory.
The trend of accumulation of the metals in the tissues is blood - Fe > Pb > Zn whereas Cu and Ni levels were not affected; Liver - Ni > Zn > Fe > Cu > Pb and Testes - Ni > Cu > Pb > Zn > Fe.
